# retry-exhausted.tflw — DEMO-FAIL FIXTURE (PLAN M1.5; updated M5 for the v2 API — v1's
# stateful `/flaky-widget` dummy endpoint doesn't exist in v2, and this file was never ported
# since dot-dirs are invisible to the `tflw check`/`run` that kept every M0-M4 milestone green):
# an intentionally-failing showcase of tflw's exhausted-retry reporting. A route that never
# exists gives a deterministic, always-failing request — `retry 1` gives 2 total attempts, both
# failing identically, a genuine hard failure and not a flaky pass. (v1's version demonstrated the
# same reporting shape against a request that *could* have succeeded on a later attempt; a
# deterministic 404 shows the same "every attempt's evidence" report structure just as well,
# without needing a dedicated stateful endpoint solely for this demo.)
#
# Lives in a dot-prefixed directory (along with the rest of tests/.demo-fail/) so a bare
# `tflw run`/`tflw check` never discovers it — tflw's `discoverTests` skips any dot-prefixed
# entry, and there's no ignore-glob config key, so this is the only way to keep an
# intentionally-failing fixture out of the default green run. Run explicitly:
#   npx tflw run tests/.demo-fail/*.tflw --tag demofail

@demofail @retryexhausted
test "a route that never exists never recovers within a too-small retry budget" retry 1
  api POST /this-route-does-not-exist body { name: "Doomed Thing" }
  expect status equals 201
